{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"107106d0-215b-4dc0-aa48-b20c2d5678c9","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, so you can use the modern patterns:\n\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via **constructor** (MSTest v3+)\n- **Sync init** — use the constructor or `[TestInitialize]`\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` returning `Task`\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client = null!;\n\n    // Constructor: TestContext injection + sync init\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Async init (runs before each test)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public void Cleanup() => _client?.Dispose();\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void Test1()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Constructor injection of `TestContext` replaces the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- `[TestInitialize]` can be `void`, `Task`, or `ValueTask`.\n- Don't mix both patterns — pick constructor injection over the property.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9c8f322f-257e-48c8-aee3-57b563970df2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended patterns are:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or a `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest v3+, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` attribute on a method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` on an `async Task` method (supported in MSTest v2+).\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. In MSTest 3.x:\n\n\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor, which is the cleanest approach\n- `[TestInitialize]` works for both sync and async per-test setup\n- `[ClassInitialize]` is available for class-level setup if needed\n\nThe modern pattern here is constructor injection for `TestContext` combined with `[TestInitialize]` for per-test setup.","outputTokens":632,"requestId":"9834:C2332:10B52DD:14FA846:69FFE117"},"id":"0c67ee9a-3030-4eec-94f3-1ab724a98560","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:36:37.567Z","parentId":"04e945ff-215a-4ce0-beb6-dd838bb7e40b"}
